05374nam a22007695i 9780231851091DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802318510917 a10.7312/ripl182342doi  a(DE-B1597)494808  a(OCoLC)1059148501  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN1998.3.B86b.R575 2017eb 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4302330922231 aRipley, Marc, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Search for Belonging :bThe Mexican Cinema of Luis Buñuel /cMarc Ripley. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b‹B›B&W Illus.: ‹/B›24.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Re-locating Buñuel’s Mexican Cinema -- tChapter 2. The Island Heterotopias of Robinson Crusoe and The Young One -- tChapter 3. Betwixt and Between: Liminal Space in La Mort en ce jardin and Simón del desierto -- tChapter 4. The Body-self in Place: The Place-worlds of Los olvidados and Nazarín -- tChapter 5. Questions of Belonging: The (Im)possibility of a Home-place -- tConclusion -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs one of the foremost Spanish directors of all time, Luis Buñuel’s filmography has been the subject of innumerable studies. Despite the fact that the twenty films he made in Mexico between 1947 and 1965 represent the most prolific stage of his career as a filmmaker, these have remained relatively neglected in writing on Buñuel and his work. This book focuses on nine of the director’s films made in Mexico in order to show that a concerted focus on space, an important aspect of the films’ narratives that is often intimated by scholars, yet rarely developed, can unlock new philosophical meaning in this rich body of work.Although in recent years Buñuel’s Mexican films have begun to enjoy a greater presence in criticism on the director, they are often segregated according to their perceived critical value, effectively creating two substrands of work: the independent movies and the studio potboilers. The interdisciplinary approach of this book unites the two, focusing on films such as Los olvidados, Nazarín, and El ángel exterminador alongside La Mort en ce jardin, The Young One, and Simón del desierto, among others. In doing so, it avoids the tropes most often associated with Buñuel’s cinema—surrealism, Catholicism, the derision of the bourgeoisie—and the approach most often invoked in analysis of these themes: psychoanalysis. Instead, this book takes inspiration from the fields of human geography, anthropology, and philosophy, applying these to film-focused readings of Buñuel’s Mexican cinema to argue that ultimately these films depict an overriding sense of placelessness, overtly or subliminally enacting a search for belonging that forces the viewer to question what it means to be in place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMotion pictureszMexicoxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2018z9783110603088oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2018 Englishz978311060397208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/ripl1823440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231851091423Cove